Q3. How does ArrayDeque differ from a standard Queue?
-->
| Feature        | Queue                     | ArrayDeque                                    |
| -------------- | ------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| Type           | Interface                 | Class                                         |
| Data Structure | Depends on implementation | Dynamic Circular Array                        |
| Insert/Delete  | Usually one end           | Both front and rear                           |
| Stack Support  | No                        | Yes                                           |
| Null Values    | Usually not allowed       | Not allowed                                   |
| Performance    | Depends on implementation | Very fast for both stack and queue operations |





Q4. Can ArrayDeque be used as both a Queue and a Stack?
-->Yes.

      ArrayDeque supports both FIFO and LIFO operations.
      
      As a Queue (FIFO)
      import java.util.*;
      
      public class Demo {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
      
              ArrayDeque<Integer> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
      
              deque.offer(10);
              deque.offer(20);
              deque.offer(30);
      
              System.out.println(deque.poll());
          }
      }
      
      Output
      
      10
      As a Stack (LIFO)
      import java.util.*;
      
      public class Demo {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
      
              ArrayDeque<Integer> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
      
              deque.push(10);
              deque.push(20);
              deque.push(30);
      
              System.out.println(deque.pop());
          }
      }
      
      Output
      
      30



      
Q5. Does ArrayDeque allow null and duplicate values? Why or why not?
-->Duplicate Elements
      
      Yes.
      
      ArrayDeque allows duplicate elements.
      
      ArrayDeque<String> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
      
      deque.add("Java");
      deque.add("Java");
      
      System.out.println(deque);
      
      Output
      
      [Java, Java]
      Null Values
      
      No.
      
      ArrayDeque does not allow null values.
      
      Reason
      
      Methods such as poll(), peek(), and remove() return null when the deque is empty. Allowing null elements would make it 
      impossible to distinguish between an actual null element and an empty deque.
      
      Example:
      
      ArrayDeque<String> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
      
      deque.add(null);
      
      Output
      
      Exception in thread "main"
      java.lang.NullPointerException




Q6. Which underlying data structure does ArrayDeque use?
-->ArrayDeque is internally implemented using a Resizable Circular Array.

    Working
        Elements are stored in a circular array.
        Two pointers (head and tail) track the front and rear.
        When the array becomes full, its capacity is automatically increased.
        
        Internal Structure
        
               Head
                 ↓
        +----+----+----+----+----+
        | 10 | 20 | 30 |    |    |
        +----+----+----+----+----+
                      ↑
                     Tail
        Advantages of Circular Array
        Fast insertion and deletion at both ends.
        Better memory utilization.
        No shifting of elements is required.
        Dynamic resizing when the array becomes full.
        
| Operation       | Time Complexity |
| --------------- | --------------- |
| `addFirst()`    | O(1)            |
| `addLast()`     | O(1)            |
| `removeFirst()` | O(1)            |
| `removeLast()`  | O(1)            |
| `peekFirst()`   | O(1)            |
| `peekLast()`    | O(1)            |


Interview Tip
ArrayDeque → Dynamic circular array, implements Deque.
Supports both Queue (FIFO) and Stack (LIFO) operations.
Allows duplicate elements but does not allow null values.
Generally faster than Stack and LinkedList for stack and queue operations because it avoids synchronization overhead and uses
an efficient circular array internally.
